      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000102493,
      "SummaryText": "em.\n\nThe facility is considered a non-responding stationary source.  In the event of fire, explosion, or a release of a regulated substance; entry within the facility or specified endpoint may pose a danger to the public and emergency responders.  All emergency responders should not enter the area except as arranged with the facility contact indicated within the RMP.\n\nProcess safety controls include excess flow valves, low-melting point fusible links to excess flow valves (fail closed), emergency shut-off devices on the system, line thermal/hydrostatic reliefs, and grounding devices.\n\nIn an effort to improve and promote system safety, CPT looks for, and seeks employee input, on process safety improvements. Additionally, the Charlotte Fire Department is contacted regarding participation in site emergency response drills."
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000102493,
      "SummaryText": "Colonial Terminals Operating Company LLC (CTOC), d/b/a Colonial Pipeline Terminals (CPT), owns a butane blending system located at 7720 Mt. Holly Road, Charlotte, North Carolina. The Charlotte Terminal Butane Blending System was constructed in accordance with National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) Code #58 (2011 edition) for Liquefied Petroleum Gas Storage and it is the facility's policy to adhere to all applicable federal, state and local laws/codes. It is the intent of the Charlotte Terminal to incorporate the most recent construction and procedural guidance into this process. If an emergency were to occur, it is the facility's policy to notify the Charlotte Fire Department or the Charlotte/Mecklenburg County Department of Emergency Management. Medical emergencies will require notification of the local Emergency Medical Services (Medic).\n\nThe CPT Charlotte Terminal complies with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) Accident Prevention Rules (40 CFR Part 68 Subpart D), the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) Process Safety Management (PSM) standard (29 CFR Part 1910.119) along with its fourteen (14) compliance elements, and all applicable state and local laws and regulations. The butane blending system is designed, constructed, and maintained in accordance with NFPA #58 and the manufacturer.\n\nThis facility has never had an accident involving the butane process which has resulted in deaths, injuries, property/environmental damage, evacuations or sheltering in place.\n\nIn the event of an emergency involving the CPT Charlotte Terminal butane blending system, it is the policy of the facility to initially contact the Charlotte Fire Department (Primary Responder) and request their assistance. The facility emergency response plans are coordinated with fire department and the Charlotte/Mecklenburg County Department of Emergency Management. The Charlotte Fire Department has participated in the initial RMP/PSM training session for this syst"
    }
  ]
